---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import MythicDivider from '../../components/MythicDivider.astro';

const toc = [
  { id: 'install', label: '1. Install' },
  { id: 'wire', label: '2. Wire into Claude Code' },
  { id: 'first-team', label: '3. Spawn your first team' },
  { id: 'deliberation', label: '4. Run a deliberation' },
  { id: 'schedules', label: '5. Schedule recurring work' },
  { id: 'loop', label: '6. Lightweight loops (no daemon)' },
  { id: 'runtime', label: '7. Pick a runtime' },
  { id: 'terminal', label: '8. Drive Zana from the terminal' },
  { id: 'recipes', label: '9. End-to-end recipes' },
  { id: 'next', label: '10. Where to next' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Docs · Get started"
  description="Install Zana, wire it into Claude Code, spawn your first team of agents, and run a deliberation — in under five minutes."
>
  <section class="container-zana py-16">
    <p class="ornament text-xs text-gold">— get started —</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3 font-display text-5xl text-forest md:text-6xl">First five minutes with Zana.</h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg text-moss leading-relaxed">
      Install the daemon, expose the MCP server, and you're ready. The
      following walks through a real first session — install, wire, spawn,
      deliberate, schedule.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-12 grid gap-12 md:grid-cols-[220px_1fr]">
      <aside class="md:sticky md:top-24 md:self-start">
        <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-gold">On this page</p>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm">
          {toc.map((t) => (
            <li><a href={`#${t.id}`} class="text-moss hover:text-forest">{t.label}</a></li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </aside>

      <article class="prose-zana max-w-prose space-y-12">
        <section id="install">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">1. Install</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Node 20+ required. Clone the repo and run the bundled installer.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="terminal" lang="bash">{`git clone https://github.com/grebmann1/zana.git
cd zana
bash scripts/install.sh

# or remote-pipe
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/grebmann1/zana/main/scripts/install.sh | bash`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">The installer handles npm install, runtime build, MCP server registration, and a guided <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana init wizard</code> for the workspace.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="wire">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">2. Wire into Claude Code</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Register the marketplace and install the two plugins. The marketplace is named <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana-marketplace</code>.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="terminal" lang="bash">{`claude plugin marketplace add /absolute/path/to/zana
claude plugin install zana@zana-marketplace        # orchestrator + daemon-driven schedules
claude plugin install zana-loop@zana-marketplace   # lightweight /loop scheduling

# verify
claude mcp list | grep zana
claude plugin details zana@zana-marketplace`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Restart Claude Code. Type <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/zana</code> and you'll see the orchestrator command, autopilot, council, ticket, schedule, and loop families.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="first-team">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">3. Spawn your first team</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Pick a topology that matches the work. For a feature: pipeline.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · /zana command" lang="text">{`/zana spawn team \\
  --members researcher,architect,coder,tester \\
  --topology pipeline \\
  --task "Add bearer-token auth to /api/v2"`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Each agent receives a sized ticket and a target ("SendMessage to <em>coder</em> when done"). You watch — you don't implement.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="deliberation">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">4. Run a deliberation</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">For high-stakes decisions: run multiple voters, preserve dissent, get a verdict with an audit trail.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · /zana command" lang="text">{`/zana deliberate \\
  --voters security-reviewer,architect,performance-engineer \\
  --question "Should we drop Node 18 support in v2.0?"`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="schedules">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">5. Schedule recurring work</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Drop one YAML file per schedule into <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">.zana/scheduler/</code>. Each file is a portable contract — drive it through the daemon (cron or interval) or through <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/loop</code>.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption=".zana/scheduler/code-and-docs-audit.yml" lang="yaml">{`id: code-and-docs-audit
name: Code + docs freshness audit
description: Spawn code-reviewer every 10 minutes against the most-recently changed file.
enabled: true

schedule:
  every: 10m            # also accepts 30s, 1h, 2d, or cron: "0 2 * * *"

action:
  type: spawn-agent     # or type: command, with command: ["bin","arg"]
  profileId: code-reviewer
  prompt: |
    Audit the most-recently changed file. Report findings as
    Blocker/Major/Minor/Nit. Read-only.

history:
  enabled: true
  retain: 24`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Reload after editing: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/zana:schedule:reload</code>. List with <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/zana:schedule:list</code>; fire one ad-hoc with <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/zana:schedule:trigger &lt;id&gt;</code>.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="loop">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">6. Lightweight loops (no daemon)</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">The <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana-loop</code> plugin drives the same YAML files via Claude Code's built-in <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/loop</code> — no daemon, no MCP, just a background sleeper. Use it when you don't want to run the long-lived daemon.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · zana-loop commands" lang="text">{`/zana:loop:define              # walk through authoring a new yml
/zana:loop:start               # pick a schedule (or 'all enabled') and arm a /loop
/zana:loop:start <scheduleId>  # arm one specific schedule
/zana:loop:stop                # kill all zana loops in this session
/zana:loop:stop <scheduleId>   # kill one specific loop`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Each loop is identified by a sentinel of the form <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">AGENT_LOOP_TICK_zana_&lt;id&gt;</code>. Cron schedules are daemon-only — <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">/zana:loop:start</code> refuses them and points you to the daemon path.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="runtime">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">7. Pick a runtime</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Zana speaks to multiple agent runtimes through a single <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">RuntimeAdapter</code> interface. Default is the Claude Code spawn adapter, which mirrors the way Claude Code itself spawns agents. You can switch via the <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">ZANA_RUNTIME</code> environment variable.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="terminal" lang="bash">{`# default — spawns agents the way Claude Code does
ZANA_RUNTIME=claude-spawn zana headless /path/to/workspace --background

# experimental — Vercel AI SDK dispatcher (Phase 3)
ZANA_RUNTIME=vercel-ai zana headless /path/to/workspace --background`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">The runtime is a clean seam: profiles, tickets, deliberation, and the MCP surface stay the same regardless of who's actually running the worker.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="terminal">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">8. Drive Zana from the terminal</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Everything you can do through Claude slash commands has a CLI mirror. Useful for scripting, CI, ops, or any context where Claude Code isn't running. After <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/install.sh</code>, the <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana</code> binary is on your <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">PATH</code>.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="terminal · zana CLI" lang="bash">{`zana --help                            # full subcommand list

# bootstrap
zana init wizard /path/to/workspace --repair-mcp

# daemon control
zana headless /path/to/workspace --background     # fork daemon (port 47402)
zana status                                        # list running daemons
zana stop --all                                    # stop every daemon

# work-tracking (need a running daemon)
zana ticket list --status backlog
zana ticket rules list
zana run list --limit 10

# scheduling (live with a daemon, also reads disk)
zana schedule list --json
zana schedule trigger code-and-docs-audit
zana schedule history code-and-docs-audit -n 5
zana schedule disable-all && zana schedule reload

# config + migrations
zana config list
zana config get system
zana config set system maxConcurrentAgents 12
zana migrate /path/to/workspace`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Two binaries are installed: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana</code> (top-level dispatcher) and <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana-daemon</code> (the long-lived process). The daemon also exposes <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana-daemon service install</code> (launchd/systemd) and <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana-daemon plugin link &lt;path&gt;</code> for plugin development. Full reference: <a href="https://github.com/grebmann1/zana/blob/main/INSTALL.md#terminal-cli-reference" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">INSTALL.md</a>.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="recipes">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">9. End-to-end recipes</h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">
            Four recipes that walk a primitive end-to-end. Every one of them is mirrored by a live integration test under <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/qa/</code> that spawns real Claude Code workers and asserts the full lifecycle. If a recipe drifts, the test fails. Full text: <a href="https://github.com/grebmann1/zana/blob/main/docs/RECIPES.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">docs/RECIPES.md</a>.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mt-8 font-display text-xl text-forest">Recurring agent on a schedule</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Drop a YAML file in <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">.zana/scheduler/</code>, reload, trigger. The MCP tool returns immediately on spawn — the agent runs detached on the daemon and lands in history when done.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption=".zana/scheduler/qa-spawn.yml" lang="yaml">{`id: qa-spawn
name: QA spawn-agent schedule
enabled: true
schedule:
  every: 24h          # or 5m, 1h, 2d — or cron: "0 2 * * *" (daemon-only)
action:
  type: spawn-agent
  profileId: researcher
  prompt: "Reply with the single word: PONG"
history:
  enabled: true
  retain: 5`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · MCP" lang="text">{`zana_schedule_trigger({ scheduleId: "qa-spawn" })
// → { ok: true, result: { status: "success", agentId, finalStatus: "pending" } }

// poll until terminated
zana_list_agents({})
zana_agent_result({ agentId })
// → { completed: true, state: "terminated", result: "PONG" }`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Live test: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/qa/run-scheduler-agent-live.sh</code> — 4/4 passing.</p>

          <h3 class="mt-10 font-display text-xl text-forest">Ticket-driven worker</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Create → claim → spawn worker → complete. Every transition is auditable on the ticket record. Priority enum is <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">critical|high|medium|low</code> (not P0/P1), and initial status is always <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">backlog</code>.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · MCP" lang="text">{`zana_ticket_create({
  title: "QA-live: confirm PONG",
  description: "Reply with PONG to confirm.",
  priority: "low"
})
// → { id, status: "backlog", … }

zana_ticket_claim({ ticketId, agentId, agentName: "QA Live" })
zana_spawn_agent({ profileId: "researcher", prompt: "Reply with the single word: PONG" })

// poll agent until state==="terminated", then:
zana_ticket_complete({
  ticketId,
  resultSummary: "Worker confirmed: PONG",
  completedBy: agentId
})
// → { ok: true, status: "done" }`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Live test: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/qa/run-ticket-live.sh</code> — 7/7 passing.</p>

          <h3 class="mt-10 font-display text-xl text-forest">Goal-driven autopilot</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Submit a goal with ordered steps and success criteria. Autopilot runs each step, an evaluator agent judges the criteria, then either settles or kicks off another iteration (default cap: 5).</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · MCP" lang="text">{`zana_autopilot_goal_driven({
  title: "Confirm two-step sequence",
  criteria: "Each step produced a non-empty answer.",
  steps: [
    { profile: "researcher", prompt: "Reply with: STEP1-OK" },
    { profile: "researcher", prompt: "Reply with: STEP2-OK" }
  ]
})
// → { goalId, status: "running" }

// poll
zana_autopilot_goal_status({ goalId })
// → { status, iteration, results: [...], lastEvaluation: "VERDICT: PASS" | "VERDICT: FAIL\\nReason: …" }

// cancel anytime
zana_autopilot_goal_cancel({ goalId })`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Live test: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/qa/run-autopilot-live.sh</code> — 6/6 passing.</p>

          <h3 class="mt-10 font-display text-xl text-forest">One-shot query and deliberation</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">For small throwaway questions: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana_oneshot_query</code>. For high-stakes decisions: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">zana_deliberate</code> — multiple voters, dissent preserved verbatim, settle-or-escalate.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="claude code · MCP" lang="text">{`// fast path
zana_oneshot_query({
  profileId: "researcher",
  prompt: "Summarize this file in one sentence.",
  timeout: 90000
})
// → "..."

// council path
zana_deliberate({
  question: "Should we drop Node 18 support in v2.0?",
  voters: ["architect", "security-reviewer", "researcher"],
  rounds: 3,
  riskTag: "high"
})
// → { id, state: "PROPOSED", _outcome: "running" }

zana_deliberation_status({ deliberationId: id })
// → { state: "SETTLED" | "ESCALATED", verdict, voters }`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-moss">Live test: <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">scripts/qa/run-runtime.sh</code> — 2/2 passing (oneshot returns PONG; cheap deliberation snap proves real Claude voters run end-to-end).</p>
          <p class="mt-4 text-moss">Want a deliberation to settle without a human in the loop? Pass <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">escalationStrategy: "judge"</code> — when the council can't reach consensus, a single <em>judge</em> agent reads the transcript (rationales + dissent verbatim) and emits a verdict, landing the deliberation on <strong>SETTLED</strong> with <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">verdictSource: "judge"</code>. <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1.5 py-0.5">riskTag: "high"</code> still requires a human regardless.</p>

          <h3 class="mt-10 font-display text-xl text-forest">More primitives in the full recipes file</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">
            Beyond the four headline recipes, <a href="https://github.com/grebmann1/zana/blob/main/docs/RECIPES.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">RECIPES.md</a> covers the full surface — every primitive below has a copy-paste-ready example with literal MCP arguments.
          </p>
          <ul class="mt-3 grid gap-x-6 gap-y-1.5 text-sm text-moss md:grid-cols-2">
            <li>· <strong>Teams</strong> — orchestrator + workers in one call</li>
            <li>· <strong>Sprints</strong> — group tickets, kanban board read</li>
            <li>· <strong>Schedule action types</strong> — <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1 py-0.5">command</code>, <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1 py-0.5">workflow</code>, <code class="rounded bg-parchment px-1 py-0.5">mcp_tool</code></li>
            <li>· <strong>Workflows</strong> — multi-step skills with templated args</li>
            <li>· <strong>Inter-agent messaging</strong> — typed messages, ack-required, inbox</li>
            <li>· <strong>Vector memory</strong> — HNSW store + tagged search</li>
            <li>· <strong>Channels &amp; events</strong> — pub/sub topics, replayable bus</li>
            <li>· <strong>Profiles &amp; skills</strong> — runtime CRUD</li>
            <li>· <strong>Module config</strong> — tune autopilot &amp; deliberation live</li>
            <li>· <strong>Checkpoints</strong> — named, resumable points inside a run</li>
            <li>· <strong>Multi-daemon swarm</strong> — spawn child daemons, broadcast, route</li>
            <li>· <strong>Validated spawn</strong> — output guardrails + auto-retry</li>
            <li>· <strong>Artifacts</strong> — versioned shared planning docs</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="mt-10 font-display text-xl text-forest">Run the live tests yourself</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-moss">Every recipe above is exercised by a real-Claude smoke test. They cost real tokens (no mocks) but are hermetic — temp workspace + isolated daemon registry.</p>
          <div class="mt-4">
            <CodeBlock caption="terminal" lang="bash">{`# preconditions: \`claude\` CLI on PATH and logged in, repo built
npm run build

bash scripts/qa/run-runtime.sh                 # oneshot + deliberation
bash scripts/qa/run-scheduler-agent-live.sh    # schedule fires real worker
bash scripts/qa/run-ticket-live.sh             # ticket lifecycle
bash scripts/qa/run-autopilot-live.sh          # goal-driven loop

# or all four (kills stale daemons between suites)
bash scripts/qa/run-live-all.sh`}</CodeBlock>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="next">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-forest">10. Where to next</h2>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-moss">
            <li>· <a href="/how-it-works/" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">How it works</a> — primitives in depth.</li>
            <li>· <a href="/features/" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">All features</a> — the full surface area.</li>
            <li>· <a href="https://github.com/grebmann1/zana" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-forest hover:text-berry">GitHub repository</a> — issues, profiles, contributions.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <MythicDivider />
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
